The defendant Leland C. Lewis was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery by Prisoners, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.20(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Leland C. Lewis in court, in custody with attorney Paul Max Moldenhauer.  John Martin Yackel appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Dr. Kent Berney PhD on the phone.  State does not have a position on competency of Mr. Lewis.  Mr. Lewis in prison setting and not on medication.  Both State and Atty Moldenhauer will rely on Dr. Berney's report.  State will also rely on Dr. Schoenecker's report.  Atty Moldenhauer takes no position on Dr. Schoenecker report.  No one wants to ask Dr. Berney any questions regarding competency.  Mr. Lewis is sworn and testifies.   State questions Mr. Lewis.  Attorney Moldenhauer interrupts and advises client to only answer questions.  State continues questioning.  State is finished.  Court questions defendant.  Attorney Moldenhauer has no questions.  Mr. Lewis steps down.  Court asks ADA what the State wants.  State asks the court to order defendant to be placed on medication and re-evaluated to set another hearing.  Attorney Moldenhauer believes client is not competent.  State would like to review statute.    Court finds defendant not competent to stand trial.  Not enough information regarding medication.  Need testimony from treating physician.
